  <TITLE> lnslt_arr_transform  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE> May, 2006 </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="lnslt_arr_transform"> filters the field through lenslet array.  </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>[dwf_out]=lnslt_arr_transform(dwf_in,lnslt_arr)  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>dwf_in  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>:input field. it must be diffractive wavefront. </SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>lnslt_arr  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: the lenslet array object. </SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>dwf_out  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: the output field or diffractive wavefront. </SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
    propagation the field to the far field of the lenslet array. 
    This propagation is effected using the Goertzel-Reinsch algorithm, 
    and wavefront pixels that straddle boundaries are properly weighted.
    By default the propagation leaves the wavefront in the focal plane 
    of the lenslet array, with Nyquist sampling. 
  </P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
	pitch=0.000252;
	a=begin(0.004,1e-6,200); 
	b=circ_ap(a,8*pitch);
	l=lnslt_array(16,16,0.012246,0.000252,32,32);
	c=lnslt_arr_transform(b,l);
	field_plot(c);
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
